<h2>Imbolc</h2>

<p>It starts with Imbolc, the time between January and the mid-February in the Northern Hemisphere and July to mid-August in the South. According to Rosie, in Scottish tradition, it is celebrated with a sense of cleaning out the old and starting the new by lighting candles in every room, on the 1st or 2nd of February.</p>

<p>The lighting on candles whether they be fire or electric (hello fairy lights), can add a bit of light and sparkle while the sun is away. And as these days can be cold and dark, Rosie recommends taking the time to take care of yourself.</p>

<p>This could be setting something to look forward to, which she was prescribed by a doctor. It could be something little or big, but focusing our mind on a happy future can help us to live it a little now.</p>

<p>Another self-care activity that&rsquo;s perfect for these times are cosy nights in. Luckily last Christmas, my partner&rsquo;s aunt and uncle gave us exactly this for Christmas, with some tasty biscuits, candles and lights. It really helped us get through the chilly dark days and made our evenings carry over the sparkling warm festivities from Christmas. So I highly recommend having fairy lights or candles to add a bit of light.</p>

