<h2>Ostara</h2>

<p>The books says that Ostara, which evolved into Easter, takes place from mid-February to March in the Northern Hemisphere and &#8230; in the South, and like Easter is celebrated around the Vernal or Spring Equinox.</p>

<p>At this time you can feel the weather start to change. The air becomes warmer, and the days are visibly getting longer.</p>

<p>As with Easter this time is about new life, with eggs, chicks and baby bunnies, and there are noticeable changes with the start of Spring. The first sign I look out for are crocuses, and then daffodils but there are other natural wonders as bright green leaves start to come out. [link to feb march wildlife list]</p>

<p>I grew up in quite a Christian house, and Easter was a really special occasion, but since moving out I haven&rsquo;t found my own way of acknowledging it. Christos annesti eggs, going to church and egg hunts or rolling eggs down a hill. How as an adult we can lose these special things. Early in my relationship we&rsquo;d buy a small pack of chocolate eggs and take turns hiding them around the place. Did it so well that a few years later we found one on the bookshelf.</p>

<p>This year, the book inspired me to mark this Spring Ostara occasion by decorating the house.</p>

<p>and I went out with my partner for Spring decorations to put around the house. It can be however grand or little you want, Rosie makes table linen and bringing spring indoors with flower arrangments of seasonal flowers like daffodils and tulips. We got a little tray with bunnies from Morrisons and some chicks and flowers from The Works. Whatever floats your boat.</p>

<p>We combined this with a Spring clean, and together it made our place feel special and rejuvinated. I highly recommend having a bit of a tidy and adding a few decorations.</p>

